  "text": "The Rust macro expansion to HIR lowering chain consists of the following key stages:\n\n1. **Macro Expansion Entry Point** (rustc_expand/src/expand.rs):\n   - `MacroExpander::expand_crate()` (line 468) is the main entry point that initiates macro expansion for the entire crate\n   - `MacroExpander::fully_expand_fragment()` (line 489) recursively expands all macro invocations in an AST fragment\n   - `MacroExpander::expand_invoc()` (line 716) handles individual macro invocations and dispatches to the appropriate macro expander (procedural or declarative)\n\n2. **Procedural Macro Expansion** (rustc_expand/src/proc_macro.rs):\n   - `BangProcMacro::expand()` (line 45) expands bang-style procedural macros (e.g., `macro!(...)`) by invoking the macro through a bridge interface\n   - `AttrProcMacro::expand()` (line 75) expands attribute-style procedural macros (e.g., `#[macro(...)]`)\n   - Both use `proc_macro_server::Rustc::new(ecx)` (line 58) to create a server for handling macro communication\n\n3. **Declarative Macro Compilation and Expansion** (rustc_expand/src/mbe/):\n   - `compile_declarative_macro()` (rustc_expand/src/mbe/macro_rules.rs, line 679) compiles a declarative macro definition into a `MacroRulesMacroExpander`\n   - `expand_macro()` (rustc_expand/src/mbe/macro_rules.rs, line 341) expands declarative macros by pattern matching the input tokens against the macro rules and selecting the matching rule\n\n4. **Token Stream Transformation** (rustc_expand/src/mbe/transcribe.rs):\n   - `transcribe()` (line 163) performs the actual token stream transformation for declarative macros, substituting metavariables and repeating sequences according to the matched macro rule\n   - Uses a stack-based approach to process token trees, handle repetitions, and maintain syntax context (hygiene)\n   - The function processes the macro's right-hand side (RHS) template, replacing `$var` metavariables with matched tokens and expanding `$(...)* ` repetition patterns\n\n5. **AST Fragment Parsing** (rustc_expand/src/expand.rs):\n   - `parse_ast_fragment()` (line 1092) parses the expanded token stream back into an appropriate AST fragment (items, expressions, statements, types, patterns, etc.)\n   - Different fragment kinds are parsed according to their context (e.g., `parse_item()`, `parse_expr()`, `parse_stmt()`)\n\n6. **Compilation Pipeline Integration** (rustc_interface/src/passes.rs):\n   - `configure_and_expand()` (line 133) orchestrates the macro expansion phase during compilation\n   - Calls `expand_crate()` (line 219) via `ecx.monotonic_expander().expand_crate(krate)`\n   - Sets up the expansion context with `ExpansionConfig` (line 205) and `ExtCtxt` (line 216)\n\n7. **AST to HIR Lowering** (rustc_ast_lowering/src/lib.rs):\n   - `lower_to_hir()` (line 485) lowers the fully expanded AST to the Higher-level Intermediate Representation (HIR)\n   - Uses `LoweringContext` (line 91) to maintain state during the lowering process\n   - Operates on the expanded AST produced by macro expansion and converts it to HIR for use in subsequent compiler passes\n\nThe complete flow is: **Parse → Macro Expansion (expand_crate) → Declarative/Procedural Macro Matching and Token Transcription → AST Fragment Parsing (parse_ast_fragment) → AST to HIR Lowering (lower_to_hir)**\n"
}

